post_text:
Dear Parents & Guardians,

Starting next week on Monday, February 10, 2020, Ocosta Lighthouse Project and Ocosta Extended Learning will be adjusting our hours from now until the end of the year.
As of right now, we load our buses at 5:00 and they normally leave the campus at 5:10. Starting next week we will be loading the buses at 5:15 and leaving campus by 5:25.
If you have any questions please contact us.

Estimados Padres y Guardianes,

A partir de la próxima semana, el lunes 10 de Febrero de 2020, Ocosta Lighthouse Project y Ocosta Extended Learning cambiaremos el horario de salida desde la semana que viene hasta fin del año.
A partir de ahora, cargamos nuestros autobuses a las 5:00 y normalmente salen de la escuela a las 5:10. A partir de la próxima semana cargaremos los autobuses a las 5:15 y saldremos de la escuela a las 5:25.
Si tiene alguna pregunta, póngase en contacto con nosotros.

post_text: Students in grades 5 - 7 are invited to join the Ocosta Math Club. We are a chapter of the Mathcounts National Math Club and will meet for mini math enrichment and math games to have fun while improving our math skills. Math club will meet Tuesdays during the After School Program from 3:15-4pm starting on May 7, 2019. Students who participate in Math Club can also elect to prepare to compete in the Mathcounts competition in Olympia in February. Click here to join! If you are not currently enrolled in the Afterschool Program please email us at ocostamathclub@gmail.com so we can get you enrolled. https://bit.ly/2IQK4iw

post_text:
When Captain Hook sends his right-hand man, Smee, on a quest to capture Peter Pan, it’s seemingly business as usual…at first. Little does Hook realize what fantastic adventures await him and his pirate posse in their search for the elusive Peter Pan. Mistaken identities, ever-morphing clouds, a classy crocodile, some very lost boys, and a fickle shadow all add to the mayhem. Meanwhile, Mr. and Mrs. Darling embark on a quest of their own and find themselves trekking everywhere from Hawaii to the North Pole in search of their three missing children. With help from the earth-friendly Neverlanders, exotic Neverland creatures, and faithful Tinker Bell, the Darling children are found, disputes are ultimately resolved, and everyone – including Captain Hook – finds a place where they truly belong.

Come enjoy the many talents of Ocosta students in this fun production on Saturday February 23. Showtimes are at 3pm and 5:30. Doors open 30 minutes before the show. Admission is $3, kids 5 & under free.

post_text: Love our bus drivers! Depend on them every day!
shared_text:
Ocosta School PTO
February 20, 2018 at 7:30 AM ·

Today I learned: The Ocosta transportation supervisor wakes up at 3:30 AM when bad weather is forecast. At that time, he drives EVERY road that our buses will have to pass; monitors the weather forecast; and then calls the district Superintendent with his recommendation by 5:30AM.

You may not be aware (I wasn't) that many of our district bus routes contain narrow, gravelly, rural, and steep roads (many surrounded by potential hazards like cranberry bogs and ditches). Navigating a 40' bus, transporting 50+ children, through these routes can be challenging in the best of circumstances. Decisions to close or delay school are made to ensure the safety of everyone involved.

Thanks to our transportation department & all the bus drivers for keeping our little ones safe every day! Thank & tag your favorite bus driver!
text:
Love our bus drivers! Depend on them every day!

Ocosta School PTO
February 20, 2018 at 7:30 AM ·

Today I learned: The Ocosta transportation supervisor wakes up at 3:30 AM when bad weather is forecast. At that time, he drives EVERY road that our buses will have to pass; monitors the weather forecast; and then calls the district Superintendent with his recommendation by 5:30AM.

You may not be aware (I wasn't) that many of our district bus routes contain narrow, gravelly, rural, and steep roads (many surrounded by potential hazards like cranberry bogs and ditches). Navigating a 40' bus, transporting 50+ children, through these routes can be challenging in the best of circumstances. Decisions to close or delay school are made to ensure the safety of everyone involved.

Thanks to our transportation department & all the bus drivers for keeping our little ones safe every day! Thank & tag your favorite bus driver!

post_text: Do you find After School Valuable?
shared_text:
AFTERSCHOOLALLIANCE.ORG
Trump doubles down: $0 for afterschool

Afterschool Alliance
May 23, 2017 at 1:00 PM ·

When President Trump first called for the elimination of afterschool funding, educators, parents, students, researchers, and policymakers from across the ideological spectrum swiftly and vocally condemned the proposal.

But the Trump administration hasn't learned. They've doubled down. Now we need to double down to make sure their devastating proposal is dead in the water when it reaches Congress.

post_text: Thank you SBAA for another wonderful year of art, special gifts and treasured memories for our students for years!
shared_text:
South Beach Arts Association
May 22, 2017 at 8:06 AM ·

The SBAA after school art program is winding down. Thank you to all who participated and taught classes for the grade school students this past school year. The last class was glass mosaics taught by Kathryn Myrsell from the Westport Aquarium.
They used many "found objects" and recycled supplies this week including beach glass, recycled glass and glass scraps from other art projects. We used leftover bamboo flooring and signage recycled from the aquarium. We used recycled glass jars and did glass on glass mosaics with clear silicon glue. We made fridge magnets with sea shells and recycled beads and glass. We also discussed healthy eating and living and students plan to grow mini garden plants in their mosaic jars to go with this weeks theme of healthy life.

post_text: About last night... 97 Students, parent volunteers, academic coaches and YMCA mentors went to Mary Poppins at the Bishop Center on The Grays Harbor College Campus. All dressed up, we loaded the buses to watch an impressive Broadway style performance that made us feel as if we had traveled to a major city. The weather was crisp and clear with no wind or rain to dampen our fancy shoes. Our students were complimented by the Bishop Center manager on their excellent behavior.(nice job parents) You could see their enjoyment by toes taping and heads bobbing as students were swept away to lively renditions of "Step in Time" and "Supercalifragilisticexpialidocious" It was a late night, with a safe bus ride home, and very memorable. Thank you to all of those that made this special evening possible.♥️👍
